<TITLE> Police issue sketches of suspected bombers in Mumbai </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 MUMBAI, Oct 26 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - Police in India's financial capital released on Friday sketches of three men who they said were suspected suicide bombers scouting the city for targets. The sketches were based on information given by a taxi driver who had taken them around the city this week, police said. The warning comes more than a year after bombs on Mumbai's rail network killed scores. The driver grew suspicious after the three men, accompanied by a woman wearing a veil, asked him to take them to prominent Mumbai landmarks. The passengers also discussed the security at the landmarks in hushed tones, a top police officer told Reuters. "The fear is three bombers could be on the loose," said Mumbai's anti-terrorism chief K.P. Raghuvanshi. India's biggest city has suffered a wave of bombings in the past two decades, including the country's worst attacks in 1993 in which 257 people were killed. Police say Islamist militants, with help from Pakistan's military spy agency, planted bombs on Mumbai's commuter trains last year, killing 187 people, including a possible bomber. Islamabad denies the char
